I think a lot about the fact that Millennials were the last generation that could build relationships with artists without being expected to critique them as well.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective consciousness for pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to think about where they came from, because back then it was hardly possible to determine that anyway.
We didn't have to question the pedestal we put them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and have influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong longing for nostalgia.
As "The Office" was still on the air, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the series together.
That was entirely different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out at once and everyone watches when they feel like it and social media posts are flagged with "spoiler warnings" or discussed in closed groups.
We unconsciously yearn for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
That's why many of us still watch series like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman" so wildly, in which there were so many one-liners that would be memes today.
We've brought all these catchphrases along, and assumed that most people already understand them.
Today, you can no longer assume that everyone knows something, even if it has massively gone viral.
There's just too much, and there's no way to systematize it. Whether we can ever get out of this oversaturation.
We're trapped in a vicious cycle, constantly discovering new content only to find out that the artist is money-hungry or a hypocrite.
That's why we have to hold onto our nostalgia and at the same time accept that the people who created the works that we enjoy can also make big mistakes.
We enter parasocial relationships with greater caution.
It's clear that becoming rich and powerful is difficult without stepping on a few toes along the way.
